    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait, that's a pretty big claim. you're saying textualism is \"the principled legal methodology\" but living constitutionalism is just \"philosophical justification for judicial activism\"? that doesn't sound neutral at all. isn't the whole point of a legal scholar to look at both sides as equally valid frameworks? it feels like you're already deciding that one is real law and the other is just politics. if a scholar says textualism is the only principled way, aren't they just picking a side?",
