      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A legal scholar's duty is to analyze the merits of arguments, but the *claim* that textualism is the only principled methodology is a strong, non-neutral assertion of a specific legal philosophy. I am stating that textualism offers a coherent, self-contained framework for legal interpretation, whereas the \"living constitution\" approach inherently requires the judge to inject contemporary societal values, which is the definition of activism. Therefore, I am not claiming one is \"real law,\" but rather that one methodology is structurally more constrained by the written text than the other.",
      "source": "target",
